///
/// "DRAWTOOLS"
@node DRAWTOOLS "Drawing tools"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Drawing tools (@{"Pic" link "Pictures/REF_PaintMethods.ilbm/main"})@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT offers lots of different drawing tools for every
        purpose (listed below from left to right). In general, the
        left mousebutton adds the brush to the layer, the right
        mouse-button deletes the brush from the layer. Cutting is
        an exception. If you draw a Bézier-curve, you can begin
        painting with the left mousebutton and continue with the
        right one in order to draw parts, even if your next click
        would no more fit into the window.

        > @{b}linked freehand paint@{ub} (1)
          Draws a continous line. You should avoid using this mode
          when @{"drawing fire" link DRAWFIRE}.

        > @{b}unlinked freehand paint@{ub} (2)
          Draws a point everywhere you draw with the mouse. The
          resulting line may not be continous.

        > @{b}line@{ub} (3)
          Draws a line.

        > @{b}unfilled ellipse@{ub} (4)
          Draws an unfilled ellipse. If you want to draw a circle,
          keep the left shift-key pressed while painting.

        > @{b}filled ellipse@{ub} (5)
          Draws a filled ellipse. If you want to draw a circle, keep
          the left shift-key pressed while paiting.

        > @{b}smear@{ub} (6)
          This function smears the original picture. @{b}THIS STEP CAN`T
          BE UNDOED!!@{ub} However, layers are not supported for this.

        > @{b}unfilled rectangle@{ub} (7)
          Draws an unfilled rectangle. If you want to draw a rectangle
          with equal width and height, keep the left shift-key pressed
          while painting.

        > @{b}filled rectangle@{ub} (8)
          Draws a filled rectangle. If you want to draw a rectangle
          with equal width and height, keep the left shift-key pressed
          while painting.

        > @{b}bevelbox@{ub} (9)
          The bevelbox-drawing-tool allows you drawing gradients. For more
          details see "@{"Bevelbox settings" link BEVELBOX}".

        > @{b}Bézier-curve@{ub} (10)
          Bézier-curves can be drawn in fxPAINT with three clicks:
          - first click (and draw!) the start and end-points of the
            curve

          - second and third click for two other points the line
            passes through.

        > @{b}flood fill@{ub} (11)
          This flood-fills the LAYER. If you want to select parts
          of the image, use the @{"magic stick" link "MAGICSTICK"}.

        > @{b}cut@{ub} (12)
          Cut and temporarily fix the select area and create a picture
          from that.
@endnode
///

/// "SETTINGS"
@node SETTINGS "Settings"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Settings@{FG text}@{BG back}
        There are many different configurations for AMIGA-systems
        and some are @{b}very@{ub} special. In order to get out the most of
        your AMIGA, you should start with adjusting the settings
        for your system.

        Options:
                > @{b}Own screen@{ub}
                  If you don`t want fxPAINT to always run on your
                  workbench and you already have selected an
                  alternative screenmode at "Screenmode" select this
                  checkbox.

                > @{b}Screenmode@{ub}
                  A click on "<" opens a requester with all available
                  screenmodes on your system. If you have a CV PPC or
                  BV PPC, the 24Bit-modes are the fastest modes for
                  24Bit-graphics-output, for Z3-boards these normally
                  are the 15- and 16bit-modes. If you own a Z2-graphics-
                  board, try out 8- and 15bit-modes - I never owned a
                  Z2-graphics-board and therefore can`t give any real
                  recommandations. It`s hard to recommend any AGA-modes
                  for fxPAINT, but if you don`t own a graphics-board, you
                  might want to try screens with 32, 64 or 256 colors.

                  @{b}NOTE: The minimum-size for screens, so that fxPAINT
                        is still usable is 640x480!@{ub}

                > @{b}Userstatus@{ub}
                  Set your degree of experience with both the AMIGA
                  and image processing software, here.

                > @{b}No requesterimages@{ub}
                  If you want to speedup the requesters (especially
                  on AGA-systems, this option is useful) by dropping
                  the nice images, select this.

                > @{b}Bubble help@{ub}
                  Switch on/off the bubble-help of fxPAINT here.

                > @{b}fxGUI Effects@{ub}
                  fxPAINT`s GUI looks great and uses full 24bit.
                  However, if you don`t like these effects and
                  want to gear back fxPAINT`s look to a look
                  similiar to the standard OS3.x-look, deselect
                  this. On 8Bit-screens, this has no effect, as
                  fxPAINT then automatically gears down.

                > @{b}Use CGX curiosity@{ub}
                  CyberGraphX (CGX) has a quite strange feature.
                  Everyone who already had a look at the autodocs of
                  CyberGraphX might have pointed out, that there are
                  different functions for scaled and immediately
                  rendered 24bit-data (ScalePixelArray) and for direct
                  output without scaling (WritePixelArray). If you now
                  believe, that scaling needs more time, you`re wrong -
                  at least for the CV 64/3D. If you check this checkbox,
                  fxPAINT will use the scaling routine without scaling
                  instead of the direct output. To get the best
                  performance for your graphics-board, check, whether
                  that curiosity exists for your board, too.

                > @{b}Picasso96 workaround@{ub}
                  Picasso96 contains a bug in its CyberGraphX-emulation
                  when emulation ScalePixelArray - the results often look
                  very unpleasant. If you activate this workaround,
                  fxPAINT will work around this bug by replacing this
                  function through a combination of internal scaling and
                  WritePixelArray.

                > @{b}Keep dimensions@{ub}
                  If this checkbox is checked, fxPAINT will render the
                  graphics in the correct dimensions and aspects on
                  the screen. This affects all picture- and penselection-
                  gadgets as well as the @{"navigator" link NAVIGATOR}.

                > @{b}Save NewIcons@{ub}
                  If this checkbox is checked, fxPAINT will create
                  thumbnail-icons for every saved image in the newicons-
                  standard. All you need to have installed in LIBS: is
                  the newicon.library, which can be found at
                   fxPAINTCD:Tools/NewIcons/NewIconsV4/Libs/HE/

                > @{b}Use tableau@{ub}
                  fxPAINT supports every tableau, that uses the OS 3.x-
                  style of transmitting pressure-data via an extended
                  IntuiMessage-structure with additional information.
                  However, if you don`t have a tableau connected to your
                  AMIGA, switch this off in order to save some micro-
                  seconds while painting.
                  NOTE: All Haage&Partner-drivers (developed by Escena)
                        are supported, as they use the systemconform and
                        officially defined OS 3.x way for tableaus.

                > @{b}Max. Tableau-Pressure@{ub}
                  Set the maximum tableau-pressure here. Note, that a higher
                  maximum results in a higher sensitivity.

                > @{b}Max. queued mouse-steps@{ub}
                  If you have a slow AMIGA, that can`t keep up with a flood
                  of mouse- or tableau-inputs, raise the value of this setting.

                > @{b}PPC merge barrier@{ub}
                  As fxPAINT also has to do context switches in order to pass
                  the mouse-input to the PPC, it can happen, that it is faster
                  to do a small calculation on the 68K instead of doing it on
                  the PPC, flush the caches and switch back. If a 68K-emulation
                  is finally available, the need for a merge-barrier might be
                  at zero, which would result in 100% PPC-usage. The value of the
                  barrier indicates the number of pixels, that have to be changed
                  before the PPC is used. Experiment with different values or set
                  it to zero, if you want to get full PPC usage (which might be
                  slower in some cases).
@endnode
///
/// "PREFS_IO"
@node PREFS_IO "Settings/Load & Save as"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Loading and saving settings@{FG text}@{BG back}
        > @{b}Load@{ub}
          Opens a filerequester and lets you load a file with options.

        > @{b}Save (as default)@{ub}
          Save the current settings.

        > @{b}Save as..@{ub}
          Save the current settings under a given filename.

        > @{b}Save layout@{ub}
          Saves the last positions and sizes of the windows of fxPAINT.
          They will appear in the same size and position the next time
          you open them.
@endnode
///

/// "DRAWFIRE"
@node DRAWFIRE "Drawing fire"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Drawing fire@{FG text}@{BG back}
        You can "draw" fire with fxPAINT easier than ever before
        on the AMIGA or any other platform. Basically, drawing
        fire is a combination of several modes:
                > draw with a special, solid pen
                > draw with "unlinked freehand paint"
                > draw with a special mode of Paint (see options)
                > draw with a special combination of colors
                  to create a gradient

        As I thought, that it`s simply too complicated and time-
        intensive to set all these settings by hand, I created the
        "Pyro Plugin" for fxPAINT. This does all the settings for
        you and offers you maximum comfort. You can select the
        gradient and the kind of the fire via one click.

        @{b}An example:@{ub}
                You want to draw a perfect looking explosion.

                > Create a blank, black image of 640x480
                > Select the Pyro Plugin from the "@{"Plugins" link PLUGINS}"-Menu.
                > Select the first type of fire (looks like a
                  sponge)
                > Select the first gradient (yellow)
                > Now start drawing in the middle of the image
                  and move the pointer in excentric circles
                  round the center of the image.
                > You should now have created a nice looking
                  explosion. Fix the image.
                > Now fill the layer, and open the fxMANAGER
                > Choose the group "Blur" and the effect "Zoom
                  blur"
                > Fix the image.
                > Fill the layer.
                > Now select group "Color transformation" and
                  effect "Correction"
                > Open the options of the effect
                > Set the Red-parameter to a value greater zero.
                  32 and 64 are good worths .. just decide yourself
                  how "hot" your picture shall look.
                > Fix the image
                > Find a possible result of this small workshop as
                  @{"fxPAINTCD:Graphics/Pictures/Workshops/Explosion.ppm" link "fxPAINTCD:Graphics/Pictures/Workshops/Explosion.ppm/main"}
                  (Example for 640x480)

                  or

                  @{"fxPAINTCD:Graphics/Pictures/Workshops/Explosion2.ppm" link "fxPAINTCD:Graphics/Pictures/Workshops/Explosion2.ppm/main"}
                  (Example for 320x240)

                  on the CD.

@endnode
///

/// "EFFECTOPTIONS"
@node EFFECTOPTIONS "Effect options"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The effect options@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The effects are organised in groups.

        · @{b}Paint@{ub}
                > @{"Paint" link FX_PAINT}

        · @{b}Artistic@{ub}
                > @{"Oil painting" link FX_OILPAINTING}
                > @{"Buttonborder" link FX_BUTTONBORDER}

        · @{b}Blur@{ub}
                > @{"Smooth" link FX_SMOOTH}
                > @{"Median" link FX_MEDIAN}
                > @{"Selective Gauss" link FX_SELECTIVEGAUSS}
                > @{"Zoom blur" link FX_ZOOMBLUR}
                > @{"Motion" link FX_MOTION}
                > @{"Gaussian blur" link FX_GAUSSBLUR}
                > @{"Minimum" link FX_MINIMUM}
                > @{"Maximum" link FX_MAXIMUM}

        · @{b}Colortransformation@{ub}
                > @{"Anti Redeye" link FX_ANTIREDEYE}
                > @{"Antique" link FX_ANTIQUE}
                > @{"Black&White" link FX_BLACKNWHITE}
                > @{"Correction" link FX_CORRECTION}
                > @{"Dithering" link FX_DITHERING}
                > @{"Gradation" link FX_GRADATION}
                > @{"MinMax" link FX_MINMAX}
                > @{"Posterize" link FX_POSTERIZE}
                > @{"Replace color" link FX_REPLACECOLOR}
                > @{"Shift RGB" link FX_SHIFTRGB}
                > @{"Invert" link FX_INVERT}
                > @{"Limit RGB" link FX_LIMITRGB}

        · @{b}Compose@{ub}
                > @{"Rub through" link FX_RUBTHROUGH}
                > @{"Texture" link FX_TEXTURE}
                > @{"Colourize" link FX_COLOURIZE}
                > @{"Compose" link FX_COMPOSE}
                > @{"Insert brush" link FX_INSERTBRUSH}
                > @{"ExploTile" link FX_EXPLOTILE}
                > @{"Mosaic (of fxALBUM)" link FX_MOSAIC}
                > @{"Bumpmap" link FX_BUMPMAP}
                > @{"Logic" link FX_LOGIC}
                > @{"Bluebox" link FX_BLUEBOX}
                > @{"Tile" link FX_TILE}

        · @{b}Distorts@{ub}
                > @{"Page Curl" link FX_PAGECURL}
                > @{"Distortion" link FX_DISTORTION}
                > @{"Wave" link FX_WAVE}
                > @{"TV Lace" link FX_TVLACE}
                > @{"Lightspeed" link FX_LIGHTSPEED}
                > @{"Earthquake" link FX_EARTHQUAKE}
                > @{"Deinterlace" link FX_DEINTERLACE}
                > @{"Fisheye" link FX_FISHEYE}

        · @{b}Light-effects@{ub}
                > @{"Lightsource" link FX_LIGHTSOURCE}
                > @{"Supernova" link FX_SUPERNOVA}

        · @{b}Matrix-Operations@{ub}
                > @{"Convolution" link FX_CONVOLUTION}
                > @{"Emboss" link FX_EMBOSS}

        · @{b}Mirror@{ub}
                > @{"Shift" link FX_SHIFT}
                > @{"Mirage" link FX_MIRAGE}
                > @{"Mirror" link FX_MIRROR}

        · @{b}Noise@{ub}
                > @{"Spread" link FX_SPREAD}
                > @{"Pixelise" link FX_PIXELISE}
                > @{"Straw" link FX_STRAW}
                > @{"Noise" link FX_NOISE}
                > @{"Remove isolated pixels" link FX_REMOVEISOLATED}
                > @{"RLE compression optimization" link FX_RLECOMPRESS}

        · @{b}Plugins@{ub}
@endnode

@node FX_PAINT "Effect options: Paint/Paint"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Paint@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect is allows normal painting with the pens.
        You are able to draw in several different modes

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Method
                        > Transparency
                          "Plain" drawing with a color.

                        > Fade
                          Drawing with two colors at once. If
                          this is selected, a gradient is created
                          from the currently selected color in
                          @{"color manager" link PALETTE} to the color set in Red/
                          Green/Blue in this requester.

                · Red
                · Green
                · Blue
                  Sets the color for Method/Fade.
@endnode

@node FX_OILPAINTING "Effect options: Artistic/Oil painting"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Oil Painting@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect performs a special version of the
        pixelise-effect that works seperatly on the R,
        G and B-components of the picture. After this
        operation is done, the picture looks like an
        oil-painting done by an artist.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Size
                  This sets the size of one "rectangle"
                  of the oil-painting.
@endnode

@node FX_BUTTONBORDER "Effect options: Artistic/Buttonborder"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Buttonborder@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        If you are regularly surfing the web, you might
        have seen lots of graphic buttons. But their look
        differs from those of AmigaOS, MacOS, Windows or
        Linux. Their borders are gradients and that looks
        cool and 3D. But creating these borders with a
        conventional image processing software might take
        some time. That`s why fxPAINT offers a special effect
        for this.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Border
                  Set the width and height of the border
                  here.

                · Change
                  You have to make a decision on whether your
                  button shall be pressed or released here. A
                  negative value creates a pressed button, a
                  positive value creates a released button.

                · Gradient
                  Check this checkbox, if you want the beveled
                  3D effect.
@endnode

@node FX_SMOOTH "Effect options: Blur/Smooth"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Smooth@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        It`s sometimes needed to smooth an image in order
        to hide "edges" in the picture or make a montage
        more realistic.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  The level, the image shall be smoothed
                  by.

                · Floody mode
                  If this checkbox is checked, the image
                  looks less blurry but is still smoothed.
@endnode

@node FX_MEDIAN "Effect options: Blur/Median"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Median@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The median-effect blurs only some parts of the
        image and makes them look different. Useful for
        some special effects.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  Set the median-level here.
@endnode

@node FX_SELECTIVEGAUSS "Effect options: Blur/Selective Gauss"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Selective Gauss@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Sometimes it isn`t possible to scan an image and
        get a high-quality picture. In most cases, a videocamera
        and a digitizer is used then. But digitised images contain
        noise in them making the image unusable for many purposes,
        e.g. printing them in a magazine. The "selective gauss"
        effect is a special variant of the gauss-effect, that
        removes that detects the noise and blurs these areas via
        a "Gaussian Blur". Note, that this effect is quite slow,
        but if you`re ready to wait, you`ll get great results.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Radius
                  Radius of the "Gaussian Blur", if applied.

                · Max delta
                  The maximum delta needed to make "Selective
                  Gauss" perform a "Gaussian Blur".
@endnode

@node FX_ZOOMBLUR "Effect options: Blur/Zoom blur"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Zoom blur@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        You hold an image right before your eyes, then move
        it away with lightspeed :) .. the image might leave
        trails as they are known from effect like "Motion Blur",
        but this time not in a certain direction but towards the
        middle of the image. This effect is then called "Zoom
        Blur".

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  The level to "Zoom Blur" by. The higher this
                  value, the heavier the effect.

                · Positiong mode
                  By default, the center of the "Zoom blur" is the
                  middle of the image. However, if you want another
                  position, check this checkbox and perform a mouse-
                  click at the new position.
@endnode

@node FX_MOTION "Effect options: Blur/Motion"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Motion@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Fast cars leave trails in the air, as our eyes can`t
        keep up with that speed. This effect is called "Motion
        Blur", whereas this effect here is a special version
        called "Motion", using an accelerated version of the
        "Motion Blur" effect that works in realtime.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  Gives the length of the created trails.
@endnode

@node FX_ANTIREDEYE "Effect options: Colortransformation/Anti Redeye"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Anti redeye@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Many photographs are made using flashes to shortly
        enlighten the surrounding and to improve the light
        situation in the room. Then, the famous "Red eye"-
        effect is created. This effect is created by our
        eyes, that are opened too wide to prevent bright
        light to be reflected. The red you`re seeing is in
        fact the blood of the people being photographed.
        To remove this effect, the "Anti Red-Eye"-effect can
        be used.

        @{b}Usage@{ub}
        fxPAINT is not able to decide, whether a red circle
        is a "red-eye" or a red point. That`s why you have
        to paint over the eyes with a small pen, then select
        the "Anti Red-Eye" effect and select a color to replace
        the red with.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Red/Green/Blue
                  Set the color to replace the red with.

                · Use current color
                  Copy the current value of the color manager
                  as "Red/Green/Blue".

                · Tolerancy
                  Select the tolerancy of the effect for what
                  has to be considered as red and be replaced.

@endnode

@node FX_ANTIQUE "Effect options: Colortransformation/Antique"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Antique@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Old grayscale-photographs have a special colortouch.
        This effect can be created with "Antique" in fxPAINT
        with a filled layer for the whole image or for selected
        areas.

        @{b}Tip:@{ub} Creates good results in combination with "@{"Noise" link FX_NOISE}".
@endnode

@node FX_BLACKNWHITE "Effect options: Colortransformation/Black&White"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Black&White@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect divides the image in black and in white
        parts.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Frontier
                  Any pixel-intensity higher than this frontier
                  is considered white, every pixel-intensity lower
                  or equal this frontier is considered black.
@endnode

@node FX_CORRECTION "Effect options: Colortransformation/Correction"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Correction@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Especially when scanning, digitising or creating own
        images, it is often needed to correct the value of
        one "color-channel" or of the whole image. This effect
        offers lots of ways to get the aimed result.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Brightness
                · Red/Green/Blue
                  Adjust the brightness of the whole image
                  and/or of a seperate channel.

                · Gamma
                  Correct the gamma-value of the whole image.

                · Contrast
                  Adjust the contrast of the whole image.
@endnode

@node FX_DITHERING "Effect options: Colortransformation/Dithering"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Dithering@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Mr. Gutenberg has made one of the greatest inventions
        of all times - he made it possible to really produce
        books instead of copying them by hand. Mr. Gutenberg`s
        invention also made it possible to print newspapers.
        But these had a problem: How shall images by printed
        with only black and white available ? This problem was
        soluted with dithering which basically simply replaces
        some pixels by a combination of black and white creating
        grayscales for the eye. However, we can print in color
        today, too and still basically use the same princinple to
        build the image of C, M, Y and K-components.

        It was quite recently that dithering became popular on
        computers though today`s graphic chips can display 24Bit
        without any problem. One reason for this is for sure the
        internet: The wide-spread file-format GIF allows only 256
        colors (and a licence ....).

        fxPAINT offers you 12 (!) different dithering methods, of
        which some can really be called an effect.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Method
                        > Bayer 16
                          This one might remind you to the good
                          old times of the A2000, it`s wordprocessors
                          and their poor display-routines. This
                          method was used in most of them.

                        > Bayer 4
                          A variation of Bayer 16.

                        > Halftone
                          Halftone-ditheirng is heavily used for
                          today`s newspapers.

                        > Rectangular
                          This dithering-method creates a unique
                          dithering, that looks as if you had first
                          created a net on the image and then filled
                          in colors.

                        > Classic
                          The results of this dithering-method
                          always remind me to pop-art.

                        > Ordered I
                          Creates good results in nearly zero time.

                        > Edgy dither
                          This one is not really dithering. It`s a
                          fast method to reduce the number of colors
                          to less than 216. The palette is always the
                          same.

                        > Direct color
                          Similiar to "Edgy dither".

                        > Ordered II
                          Might create better results than "Ordered I".
                          Better in the meaning of "less areas of the
                          image look like they were dithered".

                        > Line diffusion
                          A great and fast dithering method. But check
                          your results twice before fixing.

                        > Error diffusion
                          Good dithering results with better results
                          than "Line diffusion".

                        > Floyd Steinberg
                          This dithering-method creates the best results
                          of all dithering-methods fxPAINT offers. However,
                          it is also the slowest of all. Please keep an eye
                          on the gauge, as you should not trust in your eyes
                          to see any great differences between the original
                          and the "Floyd-Steinberg" result.

                          @{b}Tip:@{ub} Use this one for web-graphics, if you need
                               256 color images.
@endnode

@node FX_GRADATION "Effect options: Colortransformation/Gradation"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Gradation@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        "Gradation" allows you to perform a so called "Gradation
        curve" on your image. These curves are heavily used by
        graphic professionals to correct certain aspect of an
        image.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Gradientscheme
                        > Gray
                        > Red
                        > Green
                        > Blue
                          Select the channel to modify the gradation
                          curve for. If gray is selected and you make
                          any changes on the curve, the red, green and
                          blue curves are changed, too.

                · Curve
                  You can modify the curve by hand via mouse.
                  Changes are viewed in realtime, if the @{"realtime" link FXMANAGER}-
                  @{"mode" link FXMANAGER} is selected.

                · Load/Save
                  Load save a gradation-curve.
@endnode

@node FX_MINMAX "Effect options: Colortransformation/MinMax"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  MinMax@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Many images (especially scanned images) don`t always
        use the full 256 levels that could be used. MinMax
        gets out the minimum and maximum of the image and
        streches it to the full 256 levels. This makes images
        brighter and gives them more contrast.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Minimal value
                · Find value
                  The minimal brightness-value. Can be found
                  via "Find value".

                · Maximal value
                · Find value
                  The maximal brightness-value. Can be found
                  via "Find value".
@endnode

@node FX_POSTERIZE "Effect options: Colortransformation/Posterize"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Posterize@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Remind some old programs with bad display-code for
        truecolor-pictures under OCS ? This effect creates
        such an effect.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  The level of the effect
@endnode

@node FX_REPLACECOLOR "Effect options: Colortransformation/Replace color"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Replace color@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect replaces a color within a given range.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Red
                · Green
                · Blue
                · Use current color
                  The red, green and blue component of the
                  color to replace.

                · Red
                · Green
                · Blue
                · Use current color
                  The red, green and blue component of the
                  color to use as a replacement.

                · Tolerancy
                  Set the tolerance within with the color shall
                  be replaced.

                · Gradient replace
                  If you check this checkbox, the source-color`s
                  intensity is stored and used for the destination-
                  color.
@endnode

@node FX_SHIFTRGB "Effect options: Colortransformation/Shift RGB"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Shift RGB@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Systems are different. This is especially true for Intel-
        and Motorola-based machines. They use different ways to
        store bytes in memory. On Intel-based-machines, RGB-raw-
        data is stored as 0xBBGGRR whereas it is stored as
        0xRRGGBB on Motorola-based machines. In other terms,
        Motorola uses the Big Endian format and Intel the Little
        Endian format. E.g. fxPAINT internally uses the Big Endian
        format. But if you`re reading raw-data, the byte-order might
        be wrong. This can be corrected with this effect.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Shift RGB
                        > RGB->BGR
                        > RGB->BRG
                        > RGB->GBR
                        > RGB->GRB
                        > RGB->RBG
                          Possible exchanges.

@endnode

@node FX_INVERT "Effect options: Colortransformation/Invert"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Invert@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect is also often called "Negative". It creates
        the negative of an image.
@endnode

@node FX_LIMITRGB "Effect options: Colortransformation/Limit RGB"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Limit RGB@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        It often makes sense to limit the RGB-values. This
        effect cuts of values at a certain value.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Red
                · Green
                · Blue
                · Use current color
                  The red, green and blue component of the
                  minimum.

                · Red
                · Green
                · Blue
                · Use current color
                  The red, green and blue component of the
                  maximum.
@endnode

@node FX_RUBTHROUGH "Effect options: Compose/Rubthrough"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Rubthrough@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect is known to everyone who has already worked
        with a 24bit-image-processor. It allows you to rub through
        an image below your pointer.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Picture
                  Choose the picture to rubthrough

                · Transparency
                  Set the transparency of the image (shine-through
                  of the original image).

                · X-Shift
                · Y-Shift
                  X- and Y-shift of the image to the upper, left corner.

                · Use as alpha
                  If this checkbox is checked, the picture selected
                  above is also used as alpha-channel.
@endnode

@node FX_TEXTURE "Effect options: Compose/Texture"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Texture@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Textures are widely known from raytracers. They are
        the images on the objects. In this case, you can put
        a texture over your current image.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Picture
                  Select the picture to use as texture.

                · Level
                  The level/intensity of the texturization.

                · Colored
                  Use the color-information of the texture.
@endnode

@node FX_COLOURIZE "Effect options: Compose/Colourize"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Colourize@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        You can make an image appear in the currently
        selected color of the @{"Color Manager" link PALETTE} or
        of another image.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Picture
                  Select the picture, of which the color
                  information shall be used.

                · Use picture
                  Checking this checkbox makes fxPAINT use
                  the color-information of the selected
                  picture above instead of the color of the
                  @{"Color Manager" link PALETTE}.
@endnode

@node FX_COMPOSE "Effect options: Compose/Compose"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Compose@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        If you already had a look at the fxALBUM-logo, you might
        have seen examples of the "Compose"-effect. This effect
        is one of the mightiest of fxPAINT as it allows you to
        mask, combine and scale images and add glow and shadow.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · 2nd picture
                  Select the picture to combine with the current
                  picture.

                · Mask
                  If you want to mask out certain areas of the
                  2nd picture via a mask, select your mask-image
                  here.

                · Width
                · Height
                  Width and height of the "2nd picture" in percent
                  when blitted on the image.

                · Use mask
                · Mask Transparency
                  If you use a mask, you can set the frontier
                  for the mask transparency here.

                · Shadow strength
                  Set the strength of the shadow here. If you
                  set zero, no shadow is rendered, if 255 is
                  set, a black shadow is rendered.

                · Shadow softness
                  You can regulate the softness of the shadow
                  here.

                · Shadow X Move
                · Shadow Y Move
                  Move the Shadow in X- or Y-direction.

                · Glow instead of shadow
                  If this is selected, a glow-effect will be
                  added to the contours of the image instead
                  of a shadow.

                · Positioning mode
                  If this mode is switched on, you can drag
                  around the composed picture in the picture.
@endnode

@node FX_INSERTBRUSH "Effect options: Compose/Insert brush"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Insert brush@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect blits the currently selected brush
        into the image.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Positioning mode
                  If this mode is switched on, you can drag
                  around the currently selected brush in the
                  picture.
@endnode

@node FX_EXPLOTILE "Effect options: Compose/ExploTile"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  ExploTile@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Explosions are one of the favourite effects in today`s
        video-productions. Stunning titling-animations often
        contain such effects. This effect splits the picture
        into rectangles and puts them on the picture elsewhere.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · 2nd picture
                  If you select "2nd picture" as backdrop, you
                  can select the picture to use as backdrop, here.

                · Backdrop
                        > 2nd picture
                          Render the above selected picture
                          as backdrop.

                        > Black
                          Render the "explosion" on a black
                          backdrop.

                        > White
                          Render the "explosion" on a white
                          backdrop.

                        > Color
                          Render the "explosion" on a back-
                          drop filled with the current color
                          of the picture.

                · Width/Height
                  Select the width and height of the tiles.

                · Max X, Max Y
                  Maximum distance in X- and Y-direction from
                  the original position of the tiles.

@endnode

@node FX_MOSAIC "Effect options: Compose/Mosaic (of fxALBUM)"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Mosaic@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        I saw it first on the movie-banner for "The Trueman Show".
        A great picture was replaced by many, many smaller ones
        and if you stepped back one step you were seeing the original
        again. fxPAINT is the FIRST program on the AMIGA, that can
        create such effects. However, it would be quite memory-consuming,
        if all pictures were stored in full resolution in memory.
        fxPAINT`s special abilities make it possible to reduce the
        need for much memory and, at the same time store more pictures
        in memory. fxPAINT has an image-catalogisation-module called
        @{"fxALBUM" link fxALBUM}. This module has thumbnails of all pictures and
        therefore allows easy access to them and their content. So,
        if you select this effect, fxPAINT will first make some
        calculations for the fxALBUM-entries and then replace the
        image with the thumbnails.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Width/Height
                  Set the width and height of the tiles to replace.
@endnode

@node FX_BUMPMAP "Effect options: Compose/Bumpmap"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Bumpmap@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The bumpmapper creates stunning 3D-surface-effects,
        especially for logos, buttons and webdesign. The idea
        is, that you provide a picture as surface and fxPAINT
        renders a light-source on it, drops shadows, adds glow
        and puts a texture on it, if required. And of course,
        you can also change the size of the lightsource and
        whether you want to bevel the surface before calculation.
        This effect is very very mighty and you can create
        really lots of different effects, so I recommend to try
        lots of different settings if you really want to get
        out the maximum of it.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Bumpmap
                        > Bumpmap
                          Select the picture to use as bumpmap
                          here.

                        > Bevel
                          Set the bevel here. Useful to create
                          3D-letters.

                        > Radius
                          The size of the lightsource can be
                          regulated via its radius.

                        > Invert bumpmap
                          If you want high areas to be rendered
                          as low and low areas rendered as high,
                          check this checkbox.

                        > Positioning mode
                          If active, you can move around the lightsource
                          in realtime.

                · Texture
                        > Texture
                          Select the texture to put over the
                          bumpmapped areas, here.

                        > Use texture
                          Use the texture instead of the currently
                          selected color for the image.

                · Mask
                        > Mask
                          If you only want to render in e.g. some letters
                          and want the rest of the image to be unchanged
                          no matter whether you filled the whole layer or
                          not, select the mask to use here.

                        > Use mask
                          Really use the mask selected at "Mask".

                        > Invert mask
                          Invert the mask, so visible areas get invisible
                          and invisible areas get visible.


                · Effect
                        > Effect
                          You can perform one additional effect, either
                          shadow or glow. Select the one to use, here.

                        > Size
                          Select the softness/size of the effect here.

                        > Active
                          If the effect shall be rendered in, this
                          checkbox needs to be checked.
@endnode

@node FX_LOGIC "Effect options: Compose/Logic"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Logic@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        There are many ways to detect whether an image was
        manipulated or changed. This effect offers a simple
        possibility, but also allows you to add, substract etc.
        pictures from/to each other, just as if they were a
        number.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · 2nd picture
                · Mode
                        > AND
                          Combine both pictures via AND.

                        > OR
                          Combine both pictures via OR.

                        > XOR
                          Combine both pictures via XOR.

                        > CMP
                          Compare both pictures and view
                          changed areas as black.

                        > Add
                          Add the values of both pictures.

                        > Sub
                          Substract the values of both pictures.

                        > Mult
                          Multiply the values of both pictures.

                        > Div
                          Divide the values of both pictures.
@endnode

@node FX_BLUEBOX "Effect options: Compose/Bluebox"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Bluebox@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The bluebox-effect is THE TV-effect of the 90`s.
        Everytime you watch the news, a bluebox-effect is
        used to create the backdrop. The speakers are sitting
        in front of a blue screen in reality and the blue is
        replaced by the backdrop by a computer. fxPAINT offers
        excactly this effect with "Bluebox".

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · 2nd picture
                  The 2nd picture, that can be seen instead of the
                  blue or any other color.

                · Red/Green/Blue/Current color
                  The color (normally blue) to replace with the 2nd
                  picture.

                · Tolerance
                  As the video-signal contains noise, a certain
                  tolerance has to be offered by the computer. This
                  tolerance can be set here.
@endnode

@node FX_TILE "Effect options: Compose/Tile"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Tile@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect puts one image again and again on another one.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Tilable picture
                  Select the picture to paste again and again on
                  the original picture, here.

                · Width
                · Height
                  Width and height of the tiles.
@endnode

@node FX_PAGECURL "Effect options: Distorts/Page curl"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Page Curl@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect creates an effect that looks like the
        result of you taking the right, lower corner of a
        page and drag it to the upper, left corner. fxPAINT
        adds shadow and a shine to the image, too.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Red/Green/Blue/Use current color
                  Set the color of the lighting/shine here.

                · Size
                  Size of the effect.

                · Lighting
                  If checked, a lighting/shine is added to the
                  image.

@endnode

@node FX_DISTORTION "Effect options: Distorts/Distortion"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Distortion@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect stretches the image to its corners.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Distortion-algorithm
                  Choose between Radial or Quadratic.
@endnode

@node FX_WAVE "Effect options: Distorts/Wave"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Wave@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        If you throw a stone in the water, waves are created.
        Now install a cam excactly over the point, where the
        stone will hit the surface. "Wave" creates, what your
        cam might record.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Amplitude
                  Set the amplitude the image is "rotated" by
                  between two waves, here.

                · Wavelength
                  Set the distance between two waves, here.

                · Phase
                  The phase of the wave can be set here. This
                  allows you to get excactly the result you
                  want to have.

                · Complete
                  Waving an image would normally leave empty
                  areas. However, fxPAINT offers you to fill
                  these gaps with the image-data around them.
                  Check this checkbox, if you want fxPAINT to
                  fill them.

                · Positioning mode
                  If this mode is switched on, you can drag
                  around the center of the wave in the picture.
@endnode

@node FX_TVLACE "Effect options: Distorts/TV Lace"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  TV Lace@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Eye in eye with a TV screen. You don`t see a sharp
        picture, but lots of lines. Many TV spots show you,
        what that looks like. "TV Lace" creates such effects.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Unlaced
                  Set the height of the unchanged strips.

                · Laced
                  Set the height of the changed strips.

                · Change
                  Set the brightness-change of the image, here.
                  Positive values brighten it, negative values.
@endnode

@node FX_LIGHTSPEED "Effect options: Distorts/Lightspeed"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Lightspeed@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        Adds a lightspeed-effect to the image. so that
        the image looks as if it has just left behind some
        rays of light.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Max quake
                  The maximum distance from the left side
                  can be set here.
@endnode

@node FX_EARTHQUAKE "Effect options: Distorts/Earthquake"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Earthquake@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        Moves every line with a certain distance from the
        left side.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Max quake
                  The maximum distance from the left side
                  can be set here.

                · Use current color
                  Uses the current color to fill the free
                  space on the left, if checked.
@endnode

@node FX_DEINTERLACE "Effect options: Distorts/Deinterlace"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Deinterlace@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The PAL-video-signal consists of 50, the NTSC-video-
        signal of 60 half-frames per second. These are joined
        to 25 or 30 full-pictures and create a smooth motion.
        However, when two half-frames are mixed to one full-frame,
        some disturbing patterns can be created. These can be
        removed by doubling every 2nd line.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Use odd lines
                  If fxPAINT shall double the odd lines, this checkbox
                  should be checked. Otherwhise, fxPAINT doubles
                  the even lines.
@endnode

@node FX_FISHEYE "Effect options: Distorts/Fisheye"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Fisheye@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This effect makes the picture look as if you
        had looked on it through the eyes of a fish.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  The level of "fish-eying".

                · Complete
                  Complete the unchanged areas with
                  the original image.
@endnode

@node FX_LIGHTSOURCE "Effect options: Light-effects/Lightsource"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Lightsource@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Lightsources are for sure one of the most spectacular
        effects in fxPAINT. This effect adds a movable light-
        source of a given color with many options.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Radius
                  Controls the size of the lightsource

                · Rays
                  Adds small rays from the middle of the
                  lightsource.

                · Glowing ring
                  Adds a glowing ring round the lightsource.

                · Replace mode
                  Changes the method the lightsource is
                  rendered into the image. Only useful on
                  surfaces, that already have the same or
                  a similiar color.

                · Positioning mode
                  If this checkbox is checked, you can move
                  around the lightsource in realtime over the
                  image.
@endnode


@node FX_SUPERNOVA "Effect options: Light-effects/Supernova"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Supernova@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The supernova-effect can be used quite versatile.
        You can create stunning explosion effects with it
        as well as the lights of a car by night.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Radius
                  Controls the size of the supernova.

                · Rays
                  Controls the number of rays that come from
                  the middle of the supernova.

                · Positioning mode
                  If this checkbox is checked, you can move
                  around the supernova in realtime over the
                  image.
@endnode

@node FX_CONVOLUTION "Effect options: Matrix-operations/Convolution"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Convolution@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        The convolution-effect is host to at least 22 other
        effects. It allows the creation of effects via a field
        of numbers.

        @{b}How it works@{ub}
        Convolution means replacing each pixel with a weighted
        average of the nearby pixels. The weights and the area
        of the average are determined by the convolution matrix.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Field
                  Enter your values, here

                · 3x3, 5x5, 7x7
                  The size of the convolution matrix.

                · Div, Add
                  Divide the weighted result by a value or
                  add something. 0 for Div means no division.

                · Perform
                  Perform the convolution matrix on the image.

                · Load/Save
                  Load or save a convolution matrix.

@endnode

@node FX_EMBOSS "Effect options: Matrix-operations/Emboss"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Emboss@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Emboss makes the image look like a grayscale-line-
        drawing with dark and light lines.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Angle
                  Set the angle the light comes from, here.

                · Use as texture
                  Also use the image as a texture.
@endnode

@node FX_SHIFT "Effect options: Mirror/Shift"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Shift@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect shifts the image by an amount
        of pixels downwards and upwards.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · X-Shift
                · Y-Shift
                  The number of pixels to shift the
                  image down- and leftwards.
@endnode

@node FX_MIRAGE "Effect options: Mirror/Mirage"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Mirage@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Mirage is a special version of the mirror
        effect and allows interesting mirroring
        effects in photographs. E.g. a river lying
        downwards a mountain and reflecting the
        mountain chain.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Position
                  Regulate the Y-position to begin
                  mirroring at.

                · Level
                  Regulate the level the mirroring
                  is donw by. A value of zero makes
                  the mirrored picture replace the
                  original one.
@endnode

@node FX_MIRROR "Effect options: Mirror/Mirror"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Mirror@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect mirrors the image vertically and/or
        horizontally.


        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Mirror vertically
                · Mirror horizontally
                  Mirror the image round the X- and/or
                  Y-axis.
@endnode

@node FX_SPREAD "Effect options: Noise/Spread"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Spread@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect spreads the pixels around on the image,
        moving them away from the original position.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Distance
                  The maximum distance a pixel shall be
                  spreaded around.
@endnode

@node FX_PIXELISE "Effect options: Noise/Pixelise"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Pixelise@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect makes the image nearly look like
        a Greek mosaic or a picture with a small
        resolution, that was scaled to a greater
        size.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Pixel-Width
                · Pixel-Height
                  The width and height of the "pixels"/
                  "mosaic-stones".
@endnode

@node FX_STRAW "Effect options: Noise/Straw"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Straw@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        This effect spreads the pixels around on the image,
        moving them away from the original position and
        creating a trail from their original position to
        their new one. This makes the image look like if
        it consists of straw.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Distance
                  Distance between two strawed pixels.

                · Length
                  Maximum distance from the original pixel.
@endnode

@node FX_NOISE "Effect options: Noise/Noise"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Noise@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Description@{ub}
        If your TV-cable is defective, you see noise
        on your TV-screen. You might also see it, if
        you perform this effect.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Mode
                        > Replace
                          Replaces the original pixel
                          with a grayscale-value.

                        > Addition
                          Adds the grayscale-value to
                          the original pixel-value and
                          makes it look more realistic.

                · Probability
                  You can set the probability of noise
                  to appear, here.
@endnode

@node FX_REMOVEISOLATED "Effect options: Noise/Remove isolated pixels"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Remove isolated pixels@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Noised pictures are candidates for this effect.
        It detects pixels, that don`t fit to their neighbour
        and replaces them.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Level
                  Set the tolerance-level here.
@endnode

@node FX_GAUSSBLUR "Effect options: Blur/Gaussian blur"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Gaussian blur@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        fxPAINT offers you a wide variety of blur-filters.
        "Gaussian Blur" is one of the methods used by
        professionals. It creates far better results than
        some "normal" blur routine.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Radius
                  Radius of the Gaussian blur.
@endnode

@node FX_MINIMUM "Effect options: Blur/Minimum"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Minimum@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This is not really a blur-method, but the results
        are very comparable to those of blur-methods. You
        can define a X- and Y-radius in which fxPAINT shall
        find a replacement pixel with the lowest intensity.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · X-radius
                · Y-radius
                  X- and Y-radius of the filter.
@endnode

@node FX_MAXIMUM "Effect options: Blur/Maximum"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Maximum@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        This is not really a blur-method, but the results
        are very comparable to those of blur-methods. You
        can define a X- and Y-radius in which fxPAINT shall
        find a replacement pixel with the highest intensity.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · X-radius
                · Y-radius
                  X- and Y-radius of the filter.

@endnode

@node FX_RLECOMPRESS "Effect options: Noise/RLE compression optimizer"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  RLE compression optimizer@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{b}Introduction@{ub}
        Graphics take up a lot of space when stored on computers.
        Compared to audio-data, this space is gigantic. This
        problem existed already years and decades ago and so a simple,
        but fast and effective compression-method was created: RLE
        (= Run Length Encoding). E.g. if you a row of pixels

        1 1 1 1 2 2 5 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 8 8 8 8 8

        this is reduced to:

        4 * 1, 2*2, 5, 7*4, 5*8

        taking up less memory. This filter (should be performed
        on the whole image) scans your image for pixels, that are
        nearly equal. "Nearly" is defined by the tolerance you give
        this filter. You get good results (50% or more) with values
        of 1-10 when saving in RLE-formats such as TARGA or IFF-RGB8.
        Higher values can be used for fun to create strange effects on
        the image.

        @{b}Options@{ub}
                · Tolerance
                  The maximum tolerance to the neighbour pixels.
@endnode
///

/// "PICOPERATIONS"
@node PICOPERATIONS "Operations/Picture"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Operations/Picture@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The operations available here all (can) change the
        size of your image and therefore are seperated from
        all the other effects and operations.

        @{b}NOTE:@{ub} The layer is lost when one of these operations
              is performed.

        @{b}Operations:@{ub}
                > @{"Rotate" link "PIC_ROTATE"}
                > @{"Scale" link "PIC_SCALE"}
                > @{"Shear" link "PIC_SHEAR"}
                > @{"Create frame" link "PIC_CREATEFRAME"}
                > @{"Create wave" link "PIC_CREATEWAVE"}
                > @{"Clone (the exception from above)" link "PIC_CLONE"}
@endnode

@node PIC_ROTATE "Operations/Picture/Rotate"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Rotate@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Picture can be rotated with this operation.

        Options:
                > @{b}Angle@{ub}
                  The main-angle to rotate the picture
                  by is set here.

                > @{b}%@{ub}
                  The last two digits of the angle can
                  be set here. You give them in percent.
                  E.g. angle 73° and 50% gives an angle
                       of 73,5° or 73° 30'.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  If checked, gives you a small preview on
                  what the image will look like after the
                  rotation.

                > @{b}Use current color@{ub}
                  If you rotate images, free spaces are
                  created, as pictures are handled only
                  as rectangles. These spaces are filled
                  with black, if this is not checked and
                  with the currently set color in @{"color" link PALETTE}
                  @{"manager" link PALETTE}, if this is checked.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the operation.

@endnode

@node PIC_SCALE "Operations/Picture/Scale"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Scale@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Picture can be scaled with this operation.

        Options:
                > @{b}Given in@{ub}
                > @{b}Size@{ub}
                  You can scale pictures by giving the scaling
                  information in different notations:
                        > pixels
                          Absolute number of pixels for width
                          and height

                        > per cent
                          Scale width and height by per cent.
                          E.g. Halfing the size is done by
                               giving 50 twice.

                        > as factor
                          Scale width and height by multiplying
                          them with a given factor.
                          E.g. Trippling the size is done by
                               giving 3 twice.

                  The last two digits of the angle can
                  be set here. You give them in percent.
                  E.g. angle 73° and 50% gives an angle
                       of 73,5° or 73° 30'.

                > @{b}Keep dimensions@{ub}
                  If checked, the image will keep its proportions
                  and will not be "stretched" or "pressed".

                > @{b}Keep details@{ub}
                  If checked, fxPAINT performs an additional
                  operation to keep the details of a picture.
                  Check this when scaling screenshots.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the operation.

@endnode

@node PIC_SHEAR "Operations/Picture/Shear"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Shear@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Shears an image by a given angle.

        Options:
                > @{b}Angle@{ub}
                  The angle to shear the picture by is set
                  here.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  If checked, gives you a small preview on
                  what the image will look like after shear-
                  ing.

                > @{b}Use current color@{ub}
                  If pictures are sheared, free spaces are
                  created, as pictures are handled only
                  as rectangles. These spaces are filled
                  with black, if this is not checked and
                  with the currently set color in @{"color" link PALETTE}
                  @{"manager" link PALETTE}, if this is checked.

                > @{b}Switch direction@{ub}
                  Normally the angle is employed this way:

                  |  /
                  |_/
                  |/
                  +

                  if you check this button, it is employed
                  this way:
                  +
                  |\
                  |_\
                  |  \

                  In short: Puts the cutting point of the Y-axis
                            and the shear-line from bottom to top,
                            if checked.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the operation.

@endnode

@node PIC_CREATEFRAME "Operations/Picture/Create frame"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create frame@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Creates a frame round a picture.

        Sometimes it is needed to extend the dimensions
        of a picture, e.g. if you have made a screenshot
        and you want to put some text round it. This
        function was heavily used during the creation
        process of this fxPAINT documentation.

        Options:
                > @{b}X Border@{ub}
                > @{b}Y Border@{ub}
                  The size of the border to be created around
                  the picture in X- and Y-direction.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  If checked, gives you a small preview on
                  what the image will look like after the
                  additional frame.
                  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} The preview is NOT proportional to
                        the image.

                > @{b}Use current color@{ub}
                  If you rotate images, free spaces are
                  created, as pictures are handled only
                  as rectangles. These spaces are filled
                  with black, if this is not checked and
                  with the currently set color in @{"color" link PALETTE}
                  @{"manager" link PALETTE}, if this is checked.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the operation.

@endnode

@node PIC_CREATEWAVE "Operations/Picture/Create wave"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create wave@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Creates a wave pattern into the picture

        Options:
                > @{b}Distance@{ub}
                > @{b}Amplitude@{ub}
                  The horizontal and vertical amplitude
                  of the wave.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  If checked, gives you a small preview on
                  what the image will look like after wave.
                  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} The preview is NOT proportional to
                        the image.

                > @{b}Use current color@{ub}
                  If you add wave patterns to your images,
                  free spaces are created, as pictures are
                  handled only as rectangles. These spaces
                  are filled with black, if this is not
                  checked and with the currently set color
                  in @{"color manager" link PALETTE}, if this is checked.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the operation.
@endnode

@node PIC_CLONE "Operations/Picture/Clone"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Clone@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Creates a 1:1 clone of the image and its layer.
@endnode
///
/// "NAVIGATOR"
@node NAVIGATOR "Navigator"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The Navigator@{FG text}@{BG back}
        No, there is no crippled version of Netscape(tm)`s
        famous browser contained in fxPAINT (yet :). This
        navigator furthermore allows you to navigate your
        image, if it is either zoomed in or too big to fit
        on your screen. The window shows a scaled version of
        the current picture in a sizable window. The part of
        your image, that is shown in @{b}its@{ub} window is contained
        in the box, that is displayed on the image. You can
        move the box with the left mouse-button. If you release
        the mouse-button, the window of the image jumps to
        that position.
@endnode
///
/// "BEVELBOX"
@node BEVELBOX "Bevelbox"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Bevelbox@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The bevelbox tool (also see "@{"Drawing tools" link DRAWTOOLS}") allows you
        to create gradients not only with colors but also with
        effects. It creates a gradient on the layer between two
        different intensities in a certain style.

        Settings (in Pulldown-menu: Windows/Bevelbox Settings):
                > @{b}Kind@{ub} (@{"Pic" link "Pictures/REF_Bevelbox.ilbm/main"})
                  One of the following kinds of gradients:
                        > Horizontal (1)
                        > Vertical   (2)
                        > Diagonal   (3)
                        > V-Centered (4)
                        > H-Centered (5)

                > @{b}From@{ub}
                  The source-intensity of the gradient.

                > @{b}To@{ub}
                  The destination-intensity of the gradient.

                > @{b}Exchange@{ub}
                  Exchange the "From"- and "To"-values.

@endnode
///
/// "MAGICSTICK"
@node MAGICSTICK "Magic stick"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Magic stick@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The magic stick is the most useful tool for every
        professional graphician today. It allows fast,
        pixel-excact selection of parts of photographs or
        computer-created images. Basically you select a pixel
        of the image and fxPAINT selects all pixels, that
        > are linked with it
        > have a color, that lies within a settable tolerance

        The magic stick offers @{b}three ways to perform that
        selection@{ub}:
        > clear the whole layer and only select the pixels
          (no key pressed while clicking)

        > add the select pixels to the layer (Alt pressed
          while clicking)

        > subtract the select pixels from the layer (Shift
          pressed while clicking)

        @{b}Options@{ub} (Pulldowmenu: Windows/Magic Stick Settings):
        > @{b}R, G, B@{ub}
          Set the red-, green- and blue- tolerance for the
          selection.

        > @{b}All@{ub}
          Set red-, green- and blue- tolerance to the same
          value set with this slider.
@endnode
///
/// "POSITIONWINDOW"
@node POSITIONWINDOW "Position window"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Position window@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Many people need pixel-excact image-manipulation or
        drawing operations. For that purpose, they need the
        coordinates of the pointer and the width, height of
        a circle, box, etc.

        This window contains this information. Note, that
        W(Width) and H(Height) only show values making sense
        while you are painting. If you`re not painting, they
        contains the distance from your last paint-position.
@endnode
///
/// "HISTOGRAM"
@node HISTOGRAM "Histogram"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Histogram window@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This window offers you a histogram of the selected
        image. Histograms give you an overview over the
        distribution of intensities and allow you to take
        aimed measures to optimize the colors of a picture.

        Options:
                > @{b}Image@{ub}
                  Select the image you want to view the
                  histogram of, here.

                > @{b}Gray/Red/Green/Blue@{ub}
                  Select the channel of which the histogram
                  shall be created. Gray is the average of
                  red, green and blue.

                > @{b}Histogram@{ub}
                  The histogram itself. Best viewed on
                  high-/truecolor-screens.
@endnode
///
/// "PALETTE"
@node PALETTE "The color manager"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The color manager@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The color manager helps you to change the current
        color set for the current image. Its function differs
        a bit from other programs.

        The functions (from top to bottom, left to right)

        > @{b}R, G, B@{ub}
          The Red, Green and Blue parts of the color can be
          adjusted here.

        > @{b}g@{ub}
          Adjust all components (red, green and blue) at once
          to a certain grayscale-value.

        > @{b}Use@{ub}
          The currently selected palette-entry is overwritten with
          the currently set color.

        > @{b}Slider@{ub}
          You can scroll the palette entries here.

        > @{b}Palette entries@{ub}
          A click on an entries makes it the current color of the
          window.

        > @{b}Load palette@{ub}@{b}@{ub}
          A click on this button opens a filerequester, in which you can
          select a fxPAINT-palette-file to be loaded.

        > @{b}Save palette@{ub}
          Save the current palette entries as a fxPAINT-palette-file.
          Select the filename to be created in the filerequester popping
          up. If you save your palette as Storage/Palettes/Standard.pal,
          the palette entries are made standard everytime you start fxPAINT.

        > @{b}Gradient@{ub}
          This creates a gradient between two palette entries. First
          select the color which you want to create the gradient
          from. Then click on this button, so it is selected. Now
          select the destination color of the gradient and fxPAINT
          creates the gradient.

        > @{b}Exchange color@{ub}
          First select the source-color. Now make the button selected
          and click on the destination-color and fxPAINT exchanges the
          colors.

          @{b}NOTE:@{ub} "Gradient" and "Exchange color" can be used at once.

@endnode
///
/// "FXMANAGER"
@node FXMANAGER "The fxMANAGER"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The fxMANAGER@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The fxMANAGER gives you easy, fast and well organised
        access to all the image manipulation-functions of fxPAINT
        (except the ones, that change the size of the picture -
        these can be found in the @{"pulldown-menu" link PULLDOWNMENUS} at "Operations/Picture")

        From top to bottom:
                > @{b}Realtime mode@{ub}
                  If this checkbox is checked, fxPAINT recalculates the
                  effect for the whole picture after or while a change
                  is made. This mode is switched on by standard for PPC
                  environments.

                > @{b}The effect-categories@{ub}
                  Select the category of effect you want to apply here to
                  see all available effects for this category.

                > @{b}The available effects@{ub}
                  All available effects for this category are listed here.
                  The current Plugin-API doesn`t support categorisation of
                  plugins, so you`ll all find them under "Plugins".

                > @{"Options" link EFFECTOPTIONS}
                  If options exist for the current effect, the respective
                  options-window(s) will open.

@endnode
///
/// "BRUSHMANAGER"
@node BRUSHMANAGER "The Brush Manager"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The Brush Manager (@{"Pic" link "Pictures/REF_BrushManager.ilbm/main"})@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The Brush Manager is the center for everything regarding
        brushes, their selection, creation, manipulation and
        deletion.

        Functions:
                > @{"Create new brush" link BRUSH_CREATENEW} (1)
                  Creates a new brush.

                > @{"Create textbrush" link BRUSH_CREATETEXT} (2)
                  Creates a new brush containing text.

                > @{"Delete brush" link BRUSH_DELETEBRUSH} (3)
                  Deletes currently selected brush. If
                  it isn`t one of the default-brushes,
                  it is deleted from HD, too.

                > @{"Perform effect" link BRUSH_PERFORMEFFECT} (4)
                  Perform one or more effect(s) on the
                  currently selected brush.

                > @{b}Create brush from picture@{ub} (5)
                  Creates a brush from the current
                  picture.

                > @{b}Create picture from brush@{ub} (6)
                  Creates a picture from the currently
                  selected brush.

                > @{b}Scroll one step left@{ub} (7)
                > @{b}Scroll one step right@{ub} (8)
                > @{b}Currently selected brush@{ub} (9)
                > @{b}Unselected entry@{ub} (10)
                > @{b}Selected entry@{ub} (11)
@endnode

@node BRUSH_CREATENEW "Create new brush"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create new brush@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This function creates all the standard-pens in
        fxPAINT. The pens can be of different kind, size and
        density and can carry a name.

        · @{b}Kind@{ub}
                > Pencil
                  The normal pen-type.

                > Chalk
                  Create a chalk-pen with that. Don`t use too
                  high densities.

                > Detailpen
                  Creates a 100% solid, rectangular pen.
                  Size 1 creates a pen, that plots excactly
                  one pixel.

                > Artist pen
                > Artist pen II
                  Variations of an artist pen. Don`t use too
                  great sizes.

        · @{b}Name@{ub}
          For better orientation, give the pen a name.

        · @{b}Size@{ub}
          Set the size of the pen here.

        · @{b}Density@{ub}
          Set the density of the pen here. The higher the
          density, the greater the effect when painting.

        · @{b}Create@{ub}
          Finally create the pen with these settings.

@endnode

@node BRUSH_CREATETEXT "Create new textbrush"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create new textbrush@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This function allows you create a brush from a given
        text in a given font with a given style. You might wonder,
        why you can`t place the text directly on the picture
        but have to do this via creating a brush. I decided
        to solute the problem that way, because it is the
        smartest and most flexible way to solve it. E.g. if
        you put the text directly on the picture, you could not
        add glow-effects or scale and rotate it.

        · @{b}Text@{ub}
          Enter the text of the brush here.

        · @{b}Fontname@{ub}
          Enter the name of the font to be used here.

        · @{b}Fontsize@{ub}
          Enter the size of the font to be used here.

        · @{b}Choose font@{ub}
          Choose both font and fontsize via a standard-
          requester.

        · @{b}Bold/Italic/Underlined@{ub}
          Set the style of the text here.

        · @{b}Antialias@{ub}
          If you wish to have smooth edges, select this
          checkbox.
@endnode

@node BRUSH_DELETEBRUSH "Delete brush"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Delete brush@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This irreversibly deletes the brush from both disk
        and memory. If you delete a standard-brush, it will
        not be deleted from disk.
@endnode

@node BRUSH_PERFORMEFFECT "Perform effect(s) on brush"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Pen Tools: Perform effect(s) on brush@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The pen tools allow you to easily modify a brush, e.g.
        rotate or scale it. You first have to select a brush,
        then open this window. Now select one of the below
        described effects and adjust the level. If the preview
        shows the wanted result, click on "Perform" to really
        perform the action on your pen.

        · @{b}Operation@{ub}
                > Invert
                  Inverts the pen. Level must be 100 to fully invert
                  the picture.

                > Rotate
                  Rotates the pen. 0 is equal to 0 degrees. 100 is
                  equal to 360 degrees.

                > Silhouette
                  Create the silhouette of a pen.

                > Glow
                  Make the pen glow.

                > Scale (1/10)
                  Scales the pen. The size is changed by a factor, that
                  is calculated by the following formula:
                        factor = level : 10

                > Smooth
                  Smooths the pen.

        · @{b}Level@{ub}
          Adjusts the level of the operation.

        · @{b}Perform@{ub}
          Perform the selected action.

@endnode
///
/// "LAYERTOOLBOX"
@node LAYERTOOLBOX "The Layer Toolbox"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The Layer Toolbox@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The Layer Toolbox gives you easy access to some essential
        layer-operations/effects. Currently, the following is
        available:

        > @{b}Operations@{ub}
          All available operations are listed here:
                > @{"Invert" link LTOOL_INVERT}
                > @{"Smooth" link LTOOL_SMOOTH}
                > @{"Transparency" link LTOOL_TRANSPARENCY}
                > @{"Copy to picture" link LTOOL_COPYTOPICTURE}
                > @{"Copy from picture" link LTOOL_COPYFROMPICTURE}

        > @{b}Keep layer@{ub}
          If this checkbox is checked, fxPAINT keeps the layer-content
          even after a fix. This e.g. allows you to perform several
          effects on the same area of an image without having to select
          it several times.
@endnode

@node LTOOL_INVERT "Layer Toolbox: Invert"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Layer Toolbox: Invert@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This inverts the whole paint-layer.
@endnode

@node LTOOL_SMOOTH "Layer Toolbox: Smooth"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Layer Toolbox: Smooth@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Smooth opens a window:
                > @{b}Level@{ub}
                  Set the smooth-level here.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the effect on the layer.

                > @{b}Cancel@{ub}
                  Cancels the operation.
@endnode

@node LTOOL_TRANSPARENCY "Layer Toolbox: Transparency"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Layer Toolbox: Transparency@{FG text}@{BG back}
        There is not really a "transparency" for the layer.
        Internally the layer can have a high or a low intensity
        at a certain point. The highest intensity shows the
        effect at this point, the lowest intensity shows the
        original image. So, adjusting "transparency" means
        adjusting the intensity of all points on the layer.

        Transparency opens a window:
                > @{b}Level@{ub}
                  Adjust the transparency/intensity by a
                  certain value:
                        - Value > 0
                          Make the effect more intense.

                        - Value < 0
                          Make the effect less intense.

                > @{b}Perform@{ub}
                  Perform the effect on the layer.

                > @{b}Cancel@{ub}
                  Cancel the operation.
@endnode

@node LTOOL_COPYFROMPICTURE "Layer Toolbox: Copy from picture"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Layer Toolbox: Copy from picture@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This operation lets you select a picture of which
        it creates new layer-content. The colors of the image
        are all converted to grayscale.
@endnode

@node LTOOL_COPYTOPICTURE "Layer Toolbox: Copy to picture"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Layer Toolbox: Copy to picture@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This operation creates a picture from the current
        layer. In combination with "@{"Copy from picture" link LTOOL_COPYFROMPICTURE}" this
        allows you to both temporarly store layers or save and
        load them.
@endnode
///

/// "FXEXTRAS"
@node FXEXTRAS "fxEXTRAs"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxEXTRAs@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Compared with other image-processing and manipulation
        packages, fxPAINT offers a row of extra-modules, which
        enhance fxPAINT with new image-processing-facilities.

        These extra-modules are called fxEXTRAs, of which the
        following are currently available:

        > @{"fxALBUM" link "FXALBUM"}
        > @{"fxCONV" link "fxCONV"}
        > @{"fxIMAGEMAP" link "fxIMAGEMAP"}
        > @{"fxPLUGINs" link "PLUGINLAUNCHER"}
@endnode
///
/// "FXALBUM"
@node FXALBUM "fxALBUM"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxALBUM - albumize your pictures! (@{"Pic" link "Pictures/REF_fxALBUM.ilbm/main"})@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxALBUM catalogises and organizes your pictures for you. The clue
        about this is, that it is inbuilt in fxPAINT and therefore has
        optimal links with every other part of fxPAINT, including fxCONV.

        At the top of the fxALBUM is a row of buttons (from left to right):
                > @{b}New album@{ub} (1)
                  This deletes all entries in the current album from memory.

                > @{b}Load album@{ub} (2)
                  A click on this button opens a requester and lets you choose
                  an Album-file. If you already had some entries in the album,
                  you can choose, whether to add the new entries or replace the
                  old ones.

                > @{b}Save album@{ub} (3)
                  A click on this button opens a requester and lets you choose
                  a filename for the current album. fxALBUM saves RLE-compressed
                  albums - the entries are saved in full 24bit.

                > @{b}Add file@{ub} (4)
                  Choose an image in a filerequester and add it to the album.

                > @{b}Add directory@{ub} (5)
                  Choose a directory and add it and all its subdirectories to the
                  album.
                  NOTE: If you don`t supply a drive- or devicename, the path is
                        extended to the full pathname.

                > @{b}Delete entry@{ub} (6)
                  A click on this button deletes the currently selected entry.

                > @{b}Load entry@{ub} (7)
                  A click on this button loads the selected image into fxPAINT.

                > @{b}Add file to fxCONV@{ub} (8)
                  A click on this button adds the currently selected entry`s
                  file to the list of conversion-sources in @{"fxCONV" link "fxCONV"}.

                > @{"Create HTML-album" link "ALBUM_CREATEHTML"} (9)
                  Lets you save an album in JPEG/HTML-format. Note, that this
                  kind of album can`t be loaded into fxALBUM again.

                > @{b}Slideshow@{ub} (10)
                  fxALBUM shows all pictures in the best mode available on the
                  system (found via BestModeIDA) as a slideshow. You can break
                  it by clicking with the left mousebutton or by pressing ESC.

                > @{"Print the album" link "ALBUM_PRINTALBUM"} (11)
                  Print your album with fxALBUM.

                > @{b}Go back one page@{ub}       (12)
                > @{b}Go back one picture@{ub}    (13)
                > @{b}Go forward one picture@{ub} (14)
                > @{b}Go forward one page@{ub}    (15)
                  As the labels tell already.

@endnode

@node ALBUM_PRINTALBUM "fxALBUM/Print album"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxALBUM/Print album @{FG text}@{BG back}
        If @{"HTML" link ALBUM_CREATEHTML} is no choice for a system-independant overview for
        you, or if you want to have an overview over your images even
        without having the computer switched on, this function of fxALBUM
        might be of interest for you.

        Options:
                > @{b}Use internal dithering@{ub}
                  If you want your album to be printed in an acceptable
                  quality in color, select this. Enabling this option
                  together with "optimize for grayscale" @{b}might@{ub} produce
                  bad results.

                > @{b}Optimize for grayscale@{ub}
                  If you only want to print your album in grayscales,
                  select this for best quality.

                > @{b}Print album@{ub}
                  Prints the album.

        @{b}NOTE:@{ub} OS3.5 is not yet supported for this operation due to the
              way reliable 24bit-printing is supported. However, this
              might change with future versions.

@endnode

@node ALBUM_CREATEHTML "fxALBUM/Create HTML-album"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxALBUM/Create HTML-album @{FG text}@{BG back}
        Lets you save an album in JPEG/HTML-format. Note, that this
        kind of album can`t be loaded into fxALBUM again. It can be
        used to easily create a gallery for your homepage or for
        creating an overview for other platforms. fxALBUM uses tables
        hyperlinks and JPEGs - nearly every browser supports this in
        its latest version.

        Options:
                > @{b}Output dir@{ub}
                  Select the directory in which the HTML/JPEG-file(s)
                  shall be saved by a click on the "<" gadget. There
                  will be no subdirectories created!

                > @{b}Thumbnail JPEG Quality@{ub}
                  fxALBUM creates a thumbnail-image for every picture.
                  You can set the quality of this image here. A quality
                  of 40-50% should last for this kind of picture.

                > @{b}Fullpic JPEG Quality@{ub}
                  fxALBUM converts all the original pictures of the
                  thumbnails to JPEGs. Set the quality of these images
                  here. A quality of 60-75% should create good results
                  in both compression and quality.

                > @{b}Progress bar@{ub}
                  Shows you, how the works on the creation of the HTML-
                  album are progressing.

                > @{b}Create HTML-album@{ub}
                  Starts creation of the HTML-album.

@endnode
///
/// "FXCONV"
@node FXCONV "fxCONV"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxCONV@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxCONV is fxPAINT`s inbuilt mini-converter allowing you to
        easily convert whole directories and all subdirectories as
        well as single-pictures fully automatically.

        Options:
                > @{b}Source(s)@{ub}
                  All the source-material you gave fxCONV, is listed
                  here.

                > @{b}Add source@{ub}
                  Adds a source. Selecting a file will end up in its
                  conversion. If you select a directory, fxCONV will
                  convert the contents of this directory and all its
                  subdirectories.

                > @{b}Remove source@{ub}
                  Removes the currently selected "Source(s)"-entry.

                > @{b}Output dir@{ub}
                  Select the directory to which all produced output
                  shall be saved, here. Please note, that the directory-
                  structure (e.g. subdirectories) is NOT reconstructed.

                > @{b}Output format@{ub}
                  Select the format to save the files in, here.

                > @{b}JPEG Quality@{ub}
                  If the output format is JPEG, you can set the JPEG
                  Quality here.

                > @{b}Progress bar@{ub}
                  Views the progress of the operation.

                > @{b}Start conversion@{ub}
                  Starts the conversion.
@endnode
///
/// "FXIMAGEMAP"
@node FXIMAGEMAP "fxIMAGEMAP"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  fxIMAGEMAP@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxIMAGEMAP is fxPAINT`s inbuilt Imagemap-creator. Imagemaps
        are heavily used on today`s homepages. Yahoo!(tm/R) is only
        one of the famous examples: The button-bar on the top of this
        homepage allows easy access to all of its most important
        areas. If you haven`t already introduced imagemaps to your
        homepage, this is your chance!

        Options:
                > @{b}Name@{ub}
                  Enter the name of the image-map here. Never use the
                  same name for two image-maps in one HTML-source.

                > @{b}Areas@{ub}
                  All rectangle areas of the imagemap are listed here.
                  If you select an entry and then draw a box (click on
                  the upper, left corner of your aimed area, keep the left
                  mouse button pressed and drag it down to the bottom,
                  right corner) in the right part of the window, the
                  values are displayed here.

                > @{b}Add@{ub}
                  Adds another area.

                > @{b}Delete@{ub}
                  Deletes the currently selected area from the list.

                > @{b}Link to@{ub}
                  Set the destination-link of the area in "browser-notation",
                  e.g.:
                        http://www.innovative-web.de/
                     or  ftp://www.innovative-web.de/

                  Of course, other domains do exist and are possible, too ..

                > @{b}Target(frame)@{ub}
                  If you homepage uses frames, every frame has a name:
                  [..]
                  <FRAMESET SRC="[..]" NAME="DocuView">
                  [..]
                  .. in this example this frame in special has the name
                  DocuView. Enter the name of the destination-frame here,
                  and fxPAINT will expand the saved imagemap-HTML-code for
                  this. If you don`t use frames or you don`t want to link to
                  another frame, leave this field empty.

                > @{b}Save@{ub}
                  Save the HTML-sourcecode for the imagemap to a file you can
                  choose in the poping filerequester.
@endnode
///
/// "PLUGINS"
@node PLUGINS "Plugins"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Plugins@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT supports a wide array of different plugins.
        Plugins for fxPAINT that can:
        · add loaders- and savers
        · add effects
        · enhance the program with
                > a driver for tabletts not conform to
                  OS 3.x specifications
                > a mousewheel-driver
                > custom display-routines
                > toolboxes
                > anything you might think of

        The Plugins normally run in the internal multi-
        tasking of fxPAINT and can be found in the Plugins-
        Drawer. Help, a short description and more can be
        found in the "@{"About Plugins" link ABOUTPLUGINS}"-Requester
@endnode
///

/// "PLUGINLAUNCHER"
@node PLUGINLAUNCHER "The pluginlauncher"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The pluginlauncher@{FG text}@{BG back}
        The pluginlauncher displays all launchable plugins
        in this list (attention: NOT all launchable plugins
        are displayed in the pulldown-menu, as the authors
        of the plugins have to add a special flag during
        initialization .. so some plugins can only be launched
        from here). Select one and click on @{b}Launch@{ub} to
        launch the plugin.

        See also: @{"Plugins" link PLUGINS}
@endnode
///

/// "CREATENEWIMAGE"
@node CREATENEWIMAGE "Create new image"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create new image@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT offers you the ability to automatically
        create images of predefined kinds:

        > @{"Filled" link CREATE_FILLED}
        > @{"ScanQuix" link CREATE_SCANQUIX}
        > @{"VLab" link CREATE_VLAB}
        > @{"Fractal" link CREATE_FRACTAL}
        > @{"Fire" link CREATE_FIRE}
        > @{"Grab screen" link CREATE_GRABSCREEN}

@endnode

@node CREATE_FILLED "Create a blank, filled image"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Create a blank, filled image@{FG text}@{BG back}
        You can create a "blank" image here, that has
        exactly one color.

        > @{b}Standard sizes@{ub}
          You can choose a standard-size here.

        > @{b}Size@{ub}
          If you don`t want to use standard-sizes,
          enter your required dimensions here

        > @{b}Use current color@{ub}
          Fills the image with the currently used color
@endnode

@node CREATE_SCANQUIX "Scan an image"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  ScanQuix - scan an image@{FG text}@{BG back}
        ScanQuix today is the scanner standard on the AMIGA
        because of its open API via a device.

        In order to scan an image, first choose your scanner in the
        window, that pops up. Then set the rest of the options as
        you`re used to.

        When scanning has finished, the new pictures is available as
        a thumbnail in the @{"picture selection bar" link PICTURESELECTIONBAR}.
@endnode

@node CREATE_VLAB "Digitise a picture via VHI"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  VHI - digitise a picture via your digitiser@{FG text}@{BG back}
        VHI is the new standard for video-digitiser-drivers introduced by
        Innovative. You only need to have installed the VHI-driver for your
        board and then select it.

        For VLab-users:
          You will require V10 of vlab.library installed in Libs: in order
          to have support for the VLab from fxPAINT. Find this version on the
          fxPAINT-CD as fxPAINTCD:Demos/VLRec_NG/Libs/vlab.library

        The options:
                > @{b}VHI driver@{ub}
                  Select the correct driver for your digitiser here.

                > @{b}Input@{ub}
                  Choose the input the signal comes from, here.
                  Note, that the preview does only work for the
                  first three.

                > @{b}Size@{ub}
                  The capture size. Has to be reduced for NTSC.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  If this checkbox is switched on, you get a preview
                  of the incoming videosignal on the right side of
                  the window.

                > @{b}Interlace@{ub}
                  If this checkbox is enabled, fxPAINT will grab to
                  halfpictures and merge them into one - this results
                  in a high-quality grab.

                > @{b}Lum. Filter@{ub}
                  Switch on/off the luminance filter

                > @{b}Chrom. Filter@{ub}
                  Switch on/off the chrominance filter

                > @{b}Videorecorder@{ub}
                  This checkbox has to be checked, if the signal comes from
                  a videorecorder.

                > @{b}NTSC@{ub}
                  This checkbox has to be checked, if the incoming signal
                  is from an NTSC-source. The preview might not work in NTSC-
                  mode on VLab-boards.

                > @{b}Grab frame@{ub}
                  Make a grab of the currently incoming frame.
@endnode

@node CREATE_FRACTAL "Fractal"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Fractal - create fractal graphics via fxPAINT@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Fractal graphics are for sure one of the oldest, slowest and most
        exciting areas in computer graphics (if you have a PPC, fxPAINT
        will show you, that fractals can be fast, too: even realtime).

        Options:
                > @{b}Kind@{ub}
                  Select the kind of fractal to create, here. You can
                  currently choose from
                        - Mandelbrot (the classic one)
                        - Julia
                        - Tristar
                        - Phoenix Mandel (really impressing)

                > @{b}Width@{ub}
                > @{b}Height@{ub}
                  Change the width and height of the destination image

                > @{b}Iterations@{ub}
                  Number of iterations. The higher the number, the more
                  detailed the resulting graphics.

                > @{b}Reset@{ub}
                  Resets the zoom-area to the defaults.

                > @{b}The preview@{ub}
                  Click into the preview to zoom into the fractal at that point.
@endnode

@node CREATE_FIRE "Fire"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Fire - don`t burn the screen@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT can create flaming infernos for you - not only with
        special fire-tools but also as ready-to-go images. Note, that
        this effect was designed for resolutions around 320x256.

        Options:
                > @{b}Size@{ub}
                  Enter your width and height here

                > @{b}Fade type@{ub}
                  Fade 1 fades a bit stronger, Fade 2 fades
                  the flames less strong

                > @{b}Fade level@{ub}
                  The higher this value the lower the flames

                > @{b}Heat@{ub}
                  The higher this value, the wilder the flames.
                  Heat=0 is a special case.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  Creates a preview and scales it down to fit in the
                  preview area.

                > @{b}Create@{ub}
                  Creates the flames as a picture.
@endnode

@node CREATE_ "Fire"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Fire - don`t burn the screen@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT can create flaming infernos for you - not only with
        special fire-tools but also as ready-to-go images. Note, that
        this effect was designed for resolutions around 320x256.

        Options:
                > @{b}Size@{ub}
                  Enter your width and height here

                > @{b}Fade type@{ub}
                  Fade 1 fades a bit stronger, Fade 2 fades
                  the flames less strong

                > @{b}Fade level@{ub}
                  The higher this value the lower the flames

                > @{b}Heat@{ub}
                  The higher this value, the wilder the flames.
                  Heat=0 is a special case.

                > @{b}Preview@{ub}
                  Creates a preview and scales it down to fit in the
                  preview area.

                > @{b}Create@{ub}
                  Creates the flames as a picture.
@endnode

@node CREATE_GRABSCREEN "Grab screen"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Grab screen@{FG text}@{BG back}
        fxPAINT has a screengrabber built in that works with P96, CGX,
        AGA, ECS and OCS.

        > @{b}The listview@{ub}
          The window`s listview lists all screens by their names. Selecting
          one will preview it in the right part of the window.

        > @{b}Refresh@{ub}
          Refreshes the preview of the selected screen.

        > @{b}Grab@{ub}
          Create a new picture with the content of the screen.
@endnode

///
/// "LOADIMAGE"
@node LOADIMAGE "The load image requester"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Load image@{FG text}@{BG back}
        Opens an ASL-requester. Select the image you want
        to load into fxPAINT, here
@endnode
///
/// "SAVEIMAGE"
@node SAVEIMAGE "The save image requester"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The save image requester@{FG text}@{BG back}
        After this requester has opened, you can select an image
        to save and the format to save it in. Some formats offer
        additional options. Have a look at "@{"supported formats" link SUPPORTEDFORMATS}", too.
@endnode
///
/// "PRINTIMAGE"
@node PRINTIMAGE "Print image"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Print image@{FG text}@{BG back}
        You can do high-quality printouts with fxPAINT even
        on OS3.0. However, the results get stunning with OS3.5
        and a OS3.5-adapted printerdriver. fxPAINT makes use of
        the new OS3.5-functions and creates a different requester
        for that one. Some functions are missing under OS 3.5-requester
        and some under OS 3.0-requester.

        Options:
                > @{b}Unit (OS 3.5+ only)@{ub}
                  Select the printer.device unit to print to, here.
                  OS 3.5 allows to use 10 different printers without
                  changing the preferences each time.

                > @{b}Resolution@{ub}
                  Select the resolution in which you want to print your
                  image. A value of zero always makes fxPAINT use the
                  default-settings from the preferences. If you use other
                  values, the resolution is displayed below.

                > @{b}Center horizontally@{ub}
                  Centers the image horizontally.

                > @{b}Use internal dithering (OS 3.1 or earlier only)@{ub}
                  This enables internal floyd-steinberg-dithering in order
                  to optimize the printing results on older machines.

                > @{b}Optimize for grayscale (OS 3.0 or earlier only)@{ub}
                  This optimizes the image for grayscale-printing.

                > @{b}Maxmize dimensions@{ub}
                  Print out the picture as huge as possible. A rotation
                  is excluded from these measures.

                > @{b}Print@{ub}
                  Finally print the image.
@endnode
///

/// "PICTURESELECTIONBAR"
@node PICTURESELECTIONBAR "Picture selection bar"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Picture selection bar@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This bar is very useful, if you have lots of graphics
        loaded into fxPAINT. It displays all pictures currently
        in memory in the form of thumbnails. The currently
        selected picture is drawn selected, all others unselected.

        fxPAINT offers more than just this basic functionality:

        > @{b}"Iconify" the selection bar@{ub}
          A click on the bar on the left side "iconifys the whole
          selection bar to that smaller bar.

        > @{b}Mass-Iconify/Mass-Uniconify pictures@{ub}
          If you perform a click on a thumbnail with the left mouse-
          button, fxPAINT uniconifies the image, if its window isn`t
          open already. If it is already open, it`s brought to the front.

          You can iconify a picture by first activating the bar with
          a single left-mousebutton-click on a still unused area. Then perform
          clicks with the right mouse-button to iconify the pictures to their
          thumbnail.
@endnode
///
/// "ABOUTREQ"
@node ABOUTREQ "The about requester"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  The about requester@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This requester contains:
                > the version-number
                > the compilation-date
                > the copyright-notice(s)
                > the extensions found on the system
                > the inbuilt loaders and savers
                > the inbuilt fxEXTRAs
                > a small realtime-created animation,
                  if you have a PPC-board installed

        If you contact us for support, please don`t forget
        to have the version-number and compilation-date
        ready for telling us.
@endnode
///
/// "ABOUTPLUGINS"
@node ABOUTPLUGINS "About plugins"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  About plugins@{FG text}@{BG back}
        This requester gives you detailed information on
        the installed plugins, their usage (if the help-
        file(s) came with the plugin), version, author and
        task.

        Just select the plugin from the list you want to
        get information to. Some first information is then
        presented to you in the lower listview and the logo
        (if existant) is shown in the left, upper corner.

        If help is available, the help-gadget is enabled
        and a click on it shows the documentation/special
        helpfile to the plugin.

        If you have a PPC-board, you might also like the
        realtime-animation on the left border.
@endnode
///
/// "SUPPORTEDFORMATS"
@node SUPPORTEDFORMATS "Supported formats"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Supported image-formats@{FG text}@{BG back}
        @{FG shine}For reading:@{FG text}
        · @{b}BMP@{ub}
          Supported: OS/2 and Windows. 24Bit-Bitmaps
                     supported.

        · @{b}TARGA@{ub}
          Supported: Uncompressed and compressed,
                     all codecs.

        · @{b}TIFF@{ub}
          Supported codecs:
                > PackBits
                > ThunderScan
                > NeXT
                > CCITT RLE
                > CCITT RLE/W
                > CCITT Group 3
                > CCITT Group 4
                > ISO JBIG
                > SGILog
                > SGILog24
                > LZW (ready, but not linked in, because
                       of the need for a licence, that
                       we don`t own)

        · @{b}JPEG/JFIF@{ub}
          Supported: All codecs and formats, including
                     progressive JFIFs.

        · @{b}LJPG@{ub}
          Supported: All codecs.

        · @{b}PCX@{ub}
          Supported: All codecs.

        · @{b}PNM@{ub}
          Supported: PGM and PPM.

        · @{b}IFF-RGB8@{ub}
          Supported: All codecs.

        · @{b}IFF-ILBM@{ub}
          Supported: 1-8Bit, 24Bit supported. HAM6, HAM8
                     not supported.

        · @{b}IFF-YUVN@{ub}
          Supported: All codecs.

        @{FG shine}For saving:@{FG text}
        · @{b}BMP@{ub}
          Supported: Windows BMP

        · @{b}JPEG/JFIF@{ub}
          Supported: Different quality-settings

        · @{b}PNM (P5/P6)@{ub}
          Supported: P5 (grayscale) and P6 (truecolor)

        · @{b}TARGA (24Bit)@{ub}
          Supported: RLE-Compression

        · @{b}IFF-RGB8@{ub}
          Supported: RLE-Compression

        · @{b}IFF-ILBM 24@{ub}
@endnode
///

/// "QUIT"
@node QUIT "Quit fxPAINT"

@{BG fill}@{FG shine}  Quit fxPAINT@{FG text}@{BG back}
        If you haven`t entered a higher userstatus, fxPAINT
        first opens a yes/no-requester, whether you really
        want to quit fxPAINT. Note, that all open and unsaved
        pictures in memory as well as all unsaved changes to
        these will be lost.
@endnode
